		<title>By: scott</title>
		<link>http://www.scottsbasslessons.com/improvisation/shape-shifting-chord-changes.html#comment-4795</link>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[scott]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Thu, 14 Mar 2013 13:15:03 +0000</pubDate>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://scottsbasslessons.com/?p=3939#comment-4795</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[The altered notes are basically all the notes that aren&#039;t in the chord. So if the chord was G7 the chord tones would be - g, b, d, f... the altered tones would be everything except those notes. I know that sounds crazy... all the wrong notes lol! But - there&#039;s a real skill to using those wrong notes and it takes a lot of practice to make it sound convincing. That&#039;s why the minor third up shift works so well - it does the hard work for ya! ;)]]></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>The altered notes are basically all the notes that aren&#8217;t in the chord. So if the chord was G7 the chord tones would be &#8211; g, b, d, f&#8230; the altered tones would be everything except those notes. I know that sounds crazy&#8230; all the wrong notes lol! But &#8211; there&#8217;s a real skill to using those wrong notes and it takes a lot of practice to make it sound convincing. That&#8217;s why the minor third up shift works so well &#8211; it does the hard work for ya! ;)</p>
]]></content:encoded>
